{"title_page": "Kalawao County, Hawaii", "text_new": "{{short description|County in Hawaii, US}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county = Kalawao County\n| type = [[County (United States)|County]] of [[Hawaii]]\n| state = Hawaii\n| ex image = Kalaupapa penninsula.jpg\n| ex image size = 250px\n| ex image cap = Kalaupapa peninsula\n| seal = \n| founded year = 1905\n| founded date = \n| seat = none (administered by Hawaii Dept. of Health)\n| largest city wl = Kalaupapa\n| city type = community\n| area_total_sq_mi = 53\n| area_land_sq_mi = 12\n| area_water_sq_mi = 41\n| area percentage = 77.3%\n| census estimate yr = 2018\n| pop = 88\n| density_sq_mi = 7.5\n| time zone = Hawaii\n| district = 2nd\n|named for = [[Kalawao, Hawaii|Kalawao]] \n| web = \n}}\n\n'''Kalawao County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Hawaii]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaiihighways.com/FAQs-page6.htm#Kalawao|title=Is Kalawao County, on the north shore of Molokai, really a separate county?|date=2012|accessdate=January 25, 2015|author=Voss, Oscar}}</ref> It is the smallest [[County (United States)|county]] in the [[U.S. state|50 states]] both by population and land area.<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018a\">{{cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=PEP_2018_PEPANNRES&src=pt|title=American FactFinder - Results|first=U.S. Census|last=Bureau|publisher=|access-date=2019-05-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727022905/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=PEP_2018_PEPANNRES&src=pt|archive-date=2019-07-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|[[Swains Island]] in [[American Samoa]] (population 17) is the least-populous permanently-inhabited county-equivalent in the United States.<ref>https://www.britannica.com/place/Swains-Island Swains Island. Britannica.com. Retrieved September 5, 2019.</ref><ref>https://www2.census.gov/geo/pdfs/reference/GARM/Ch4GARM.pdf States, Counties, and Statistically Equivalent Entities (Chapter 4). Census.gov. Retrieved September 5, 2019.</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20170628232229/https://www.census.gov/geo/reference/codes/cou.html U.S. Census Bureau. 2010 FIPS Codes for Counties and County Equivalent Entities (archived). Retrieved September 5, 2019.</ref> [[Kingman Reef]], with a land area of 0.03 square kilometers,<ref>https://www.britannica.com/place/Kingman-Reef Britannica.com. Kingman Reef. Retrieved September 5, 2019.</ref> is the smallest county-equivalent in the U.S. by land area.}} The county encompasses the [[Kalaupapa Peninsula|Kalaupapa or Makanalua Peninsula]], on the north coast of the island of [[Molokai|Moloka{{okina}}i]]. The small peninsula is isolated from the rest of Moloka{{okina}}i by cliffs over a quarter-mile high&mdash;the only land access is a [[mule]] trail.\n\nBecause of the small population, Kalawao County does not have the functions of other Hawaii counties. Instead, it is a judicial district of [[Maui County, Hawaii|Maui County]], which includes the rest of the island of Moloka{{okina}}i. The county has no elected government.\n\nIt was developed and used from 1866 to 1969 for settlements for treatment of quarantined persons with [[Hansen's disease]] (leprosy).\n\n==History==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2017}}\nThe [[Kingdom of Hawaii|Kingdom of Hawai{{okina}}i]], the [[Republic of Hawaii|Republic of Hawai{{okina}}i]], the [[Territory of Hawaii|territory]], and the state of Hawaii exiled persons suffering from [[Hansen's disease]] to the peninsula, from 1866 to 1969. The [[quarantine]] policy was lifted after effective [[Antibiotics|antibiotic]] treatments were developed that could be administered on an outpatient basis and patients could be rendered non-contagious.\n\nMany of the residents chose to remain on the peninsula, as they believed their disfigurements from the illness would make reintegration into society impossible. The state promised that they could live there for the rest of their lives. No new patients, or other permanent residents, were later admitted. Visitors are permitted only as part of official tours. State law prohibits anyone under the age of 16 from visiting or living there, although exceptions have been made for children visiting their relatives.\n\nThe [[Kalaupapa National Historical Park]] was established to preserve the county's history and environment. It is coterminous with the boundaries of Kalawao County.\n\n==Government==\nKalawao County lacks a local, county government. Instead, Kalawao County is administered by the [[Hawaii Department of Health]] because of the history of the settlement and current patients living there. Under Hawaiian state law, the Director of the Hawaii Department of Health, who is appointed by the [[Governor of Hawaii|Governor]], also serves as the [[Mayor of Kalawao County]].<ref name=hadvertiser>{{cite news|first=Robbie|last=Dingeman|title=Smallest county to ban smoking |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2002/Oct/31/ln/ln22a.html |work=[[Honolulu Advertiser]] |date=2002-10-31 |accessdate=2014-01-02}}</ref><ref name=time>{{cite news|first=Nate|last=Rawlings|title=Hawaii Official Killed in Plane Crash |url=http://nation.time.com/2013/12/12/hawaii-official-killed-in-plane-crash/ |work=[[Time Magazine]] |date=2013-12-12 |accessdate=2014-01-02}}</ref><ref name=khon>{{cite news |first=Kristine |last=Uyeno |title=Hawaii Official Killed in Plane Crash |url=http://www.khon2.com/news/loretta-fuddy-committed-to-serving-others |work=[[KHON-TV|KHON]] |date=2013-12-12 |accessdate=2014-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104142321/http://www.khon2.com/news/loretta-fuddy-committed-to-serving-others |archivedate=2014-01-04 }}</ref><ref name=hsa>{{cite news |first=Gregg K. |last=Kakesako |title=Pilot described 'catastrophic engine failure' in Molokai crash |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/breaking/235590541.html?id=235590541 |work=[[Honolulu Star Advertiser]] |date=2013-12-12 |accessdate=2014-01-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131221154659/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/breaking/235590541.html?id=235590541 |archivedate=2013-12-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The Mayor holds executive powers within the county; the mayor also appoints a county [[Sheriffs in the United States|sheriff]], who is selected from local residents.<ref name=\"doh\">{{cite web |url=http://hawaii.gov/health/about/doh-info.html |title=Department of Health Administrative Offices |publisher=State of Hawai\u02bbi |accessdate=2010-09-28}}</ref> The only county statutes that apply to Kalawao County directly are those on matters of health.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chem.hawaii.edu/uham/counties.html|title=Hawaii's 4 (or 5) Counties|accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n\nKalawao is part of the First Judicial Circuit, which includes the entire island of [[Oahu]].<ref>\"The Judiciary - State of Hawaii - Annual Report - July 1, 1986 to June 30, 1987\". p16 and p26. https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/Digitization/109520NCJRS.pdf</ref> For the purpose of notarization, the designated venue for the First Judicial Circuit is \"State of Hawaii, City and County of Honolulu.\"\n\n==Geography==\n\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|53|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|12|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|41|sqmi}} (77.3%) is water.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020527061848/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|archive-date=2002-05-27|url-status=dead}}</ref> By land area, it is the [[County statistics of the United States#Smallest counties by land area nationwide|smallest true county in the United States]]; [[Falls Church, Virginia]] is smaller, but is an [[independent city]] with county-level governance and is not a county or part of one.\n\n===Kalaupapa Peninsula===\nKalaupapa Peninsula contains the county's only settlement, [[Kalaupapa, Hawaii|Kalaupapa]]. The Kalaupapa Peninsula developed from lava that erupted from the ocean floor near [[Kauhak\u014d Crater]] and spread outward, forming a low [[shield volcano]]. This was the most recent volcanic episode on the island and of the larger [[East Molokai|East Moloka{{okina}}i]] shield volcano, occurring after the formation of the cliffs by erosion.\n\n===Subdivisions===\n{{Outdated section|date = September 2014|reason = This section gives a population of 139, but the population is only 90}}\n\nKalawao County is composed of four [[ahupua\u02bba]]. From west to east:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.city-data.com/neighborhood/Kalaupapa-Ahupua-a-Kalaupapa-HI.html|title=Kalaupapa Ahupua`a neighborhood in Kalaupapa, Hawaii (HI), 96742 subdivision profile - real estate, apartments, condos, homes, community, population, jobs, income, streets|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.city-data.com/neighborhood/Waikolu-Ahupua-a-Kaunakakai-HI.html|title=Waikolu Ahupua`a neighborhood in Kaunakakai, Hawaii (HI), 96742 subdivision profile - real estate, apartments, condos, homes, community, population, jobs, income, streets|publisher=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-style=\"background: #CCC;\"\n! align=\"left\" |''Ahupua\u02bba'' || Area<br />mi<sup>2</sup> || Area<br />km<sup>2</sup> || Population\n!Description\n|-\n| [[Kalaupapa, Hawaii|Kalaupapa]] || align=\"right\"|  2.079 || align=\"right\"|  5.385 || align=\"right\"| 122\n|West side of Kalaupapa peninsula. Includes a section of Moloka\u02bbi's coast further west\n|-\n| [[Makanalua, Hawaii|Makanalua]] || align=\"right\"|  3.229 || align=\"right\"|  8.363 || align=\"right\"| 8\n|Strip of land in the center of the peninsula that runs to its northern tip. Includes [[Kalaupapa Airport]].\n|-\n| [[Kalawao, Hawaii|Kalawao]] || align=\"right\"|  3.294 || align=\"right\"|  8.531 || align=\"right\"| 9\n|Eastern coast of Kalaupapa peninsula and Waialeia Valley to the southeast\n|-\n| [[Waikolu, Hawaii|Waikolu]] || align=\"right\"|  5.544 || align=\"right\"|  14.359 || align=\"right\"| 0\n|Includes namesake valley. Uninhabited.<ref>[http://manoa.hawaii.edu/hpicesu/techr/135/08.pdf Mark D. McCoy: ''The Lands of the Hina: An Archeological Overview and Assessment of Kalaupapa National Historical Park, Moloka{{Okina}}i,'' Chapter 8: Assessment] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110901015953/http://manoa.hawaii.edu/hpicesu/techr/135/08.pdf |date=2011-09-01 }}, Seite 33</ref>\n|-\n|-style=\"background: #DDD;\" | class=\"sortbottom\"\n|Kalawao County|| align=\"right\"| 14.146 || align=\"right\"| 36.638 || align=\"right\"| 139\n|\n|}\n\n===Demographics===\n{{US Census population\n|1900= 1177\n|1910= 785\n|1920= 667\n|1930= 605\n|1940= 446\n|1950= 340\n|1960= 279\n|1970= 172\n|1980= 144\n|1990= 130\n|2000= 147\n|2010= 90\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=88\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 28, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=June 28, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/hi190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 28, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 28, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2018<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/15/15005.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 28, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606183851/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/15/15005.html|archivedate=June 6, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]] of 2000,<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> 147 people, 115 households, and 21 families resided in the county, declining to 90 inhabitants in 2010. The [[population density]] was 11 people per square mile (4/km<sup>2</sup>). The 172 housing units produced an average density of 13 per square&nbsp;mile (5/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the county was 25.85% [[Race (U.S. census)|White]], 17.01% [[Race (U.S. census)|Asian]], 48.30% [[Race (U.S. census)|Pacific Islander]], 2.72% from [[race (U.S. census)|other races]], and 6.12% from two or more races. [[Race (U.S. census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (U.S. census)|Latino]] of any race made up 4.08%.\n\n1.70% of households housed children under the age of 18. 16.50% were married couples living together. 2.60% had a female householder with no husband present. 80.90% were non-families. 79.10% of all households were made up of individuals and 31.30% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 1.28 and the average family size was 2.27.\n\n2.00%  under the age of 18, 1.40% from 18 to 24, 18.40% from 25 to 44, 46.30% from 45 to 64, and 32.00% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 59 years. For every 100 females, there were 98.60 males. The population has declined since 1900:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/hi190090.txt|title=Bureau of the Census: HAWAII. Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:600 height:200\nPlotArea = width:80% height:70% left:20% bottom:20%\nAlignBars = late\n\nDateFormat = yyyy\nPeriod = from:0 till:1200\nTimeAxis = orientation:vertical\nScaleMajor = increment:200 start:0\n\nPlotData=\n color:drabgreen \n bar:1900 from:start till:1177\n bar:1910 from:start till:785\n bar:1920 from:start till:667\n bar:1930 from:start till:605\n bar:1940 from:start till:446\n bar:1950 from:start till:370\n bar:1960 from:start till:279\n bar:1970 from:start till:172\n bar:1980 from:start till:144\n bar:1990 from:start till:130\n bar:2000 from:start till:147\n bar:2010 from:start till:90\n bar:2018 from:start till:88\n\nTextData=\n pos:(100,190) fontsize:M text:Population at censuses of 1900 through 2010\n</timeline>\n\nCurrent residents include 16 former patients,<ref>[http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/29011284/kalaupapa-the-place-the-people-the-plan-for-the-future Planning for Kalaupapa's future means remembering its past]</ref> 40 federal employees who work on preservation projects, and some state-employed health workers.<ref>[https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2015/05/when-the-last-patient-dies/394163/ When the Last Patient Dies]</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nThe only access to Kalawao County is by air, or by a steep mule trail that descends 1,600 feet from the rest of Moloka{{okina}}i.  [[Kalaupapa Airport]] has scheduled air service to [[Molokai Airport|Moloka{{okina}}i Airport]] and to [[Honolulu Airport]].\n\nFreight is delivered to the county once a year, usually in July, by barge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/kala/historyculture/life2day.htm|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|title=Life Today in Kalaupapa|accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:95%;\"\n|+ '''Kalawao County vote<br /> by party in presidential elections'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|first=David|last=Leip|website=uselectionatlas.org|accessdate=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n|- style=''background:lightgrey;''\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n!Others\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2016 United States presidential election in Hawaii|2016]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|5.00% ''1''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''70.00%''' ''14''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|25.00% ''5''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2012 United States presidential election in Hawaii|2012]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|7.41% ''2''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''92.59%''' ''25''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|0% ''0''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2008 United States presidential election in Hawaii|2008]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|19.35% ''6''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''77.42%''' ''24''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|3.23% ''1''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2004 United States presidential election in Hawaii|2004]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|35.00% ''14''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''65.00%''' ''26''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|0% ''0''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2000 United States presidential election in Hawaii|2000]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|24.44% ''11''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''66.67%''' ''30''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|8.89% ''4''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1996 United States presidential election in Hawaii|1996]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|20.63% ''13''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''73.02%''' ''46''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|6.35% ''4''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1992 United States presidential election in Hawaii|1992]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|32.00% ''24''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''64.00%''' ''48''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|4.00% ''3''\n|}\nLike the rest of the state, Kalawao County is a stronghold for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], despite the small number of total votes. It was the only county in the United States where the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate in the [[2016 United States Presidential election]], [[Donald Trump]], finished in third only getting one vote; 70% of Kalawao's voters chose Democratic nominee [[Hillary Clinton]], and 25% of Kalawao voters cast their ballots for [[Green Party (United States)|Green]] candidate [[Jill Stein]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Statewide Precinct Detail |url=http://files.hawaii.gov/elections/files/results/2016/general/precinct.pdf |publisher=State of Hawaii Office of Elections |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Kalawao County}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Kalawao County, Molokai, Hawaii\n|North     = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n|Northeast = \n|East      = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n|Southeast = \n|South     = [[Maui County, Hawaii|Maui County]]\n|Southwest = \n|West      = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n|Northwest = \n}}\n\n{{Kalawao County, Hawaii}}\n{{Hawaii}}\n{{Western U.S. majority-minority counties}}{{Authority control}}\n{{coord|21|11|49|N|156|58|02|W|region:US-HI_type:adm2nd_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Kalawao County, Hawaii| ]]\n[[Category:Molokai]]\n[[Category:Hawaii counties]]\n[[Category:1905 establishments in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1905]]\n[[Category:Maui County, Hawaii]]\n\u2190\u2014\n", "text_old": "{{short description|County in Hawaii, US}}\n{{Infobox U.S. county\n| county = Kalawao County\n| type = [[County (United States)|County]] of [[Hawaii]]\n| state = Hawaii\n| ex image = Kalaupapa penninsula.jpg\n| ex image size = 250px\n| ex image cap = Kalaupapa peninsula\n| seal = \n| founded year = 1905\n| founded date = \n| seat = none (administered by Hawaii Dept. of Health)\n| largest city wl = Kalaupapa\n| city type = community\n| area_total_sq_mi = 53\n| area_land_sq_mi = 12\n| area_water_sq_mi = 41\n| area percentage = 77.3%\n| census estimate yr = 2018\n| pop = 88\n| density_sq_mi = 7.5\n| time zone = Hawaii\n| district = 2nd\n|named for = [[Kalawao, Hawaii|Kalawao]] \n| web = \n}}\n\n'''Kalawao County''' is a [[County (United States)|county]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Hawaii]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hawaiihighways.com/FAQs-page6.htm#Kalawao|title=Is Kalawao County, on the north shore of Molokai, really a separate county?|date=2012|accessdate=January 25, 2015|author=Voss, Oscar}}</ref> It is the smallest [[County (United States)|county]] in the [[U.S. state|50 states]] both by population and land area.<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018a\">{{cite web|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=PEP_2018_PEPANNRES&src=pt|title=American FactFinder - Results|first=U.S. Census|last=Bureau|publisher=|access-date=2019-05-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190727022905/https://factfinder.census.gov/faces/tableservices/jsf/pages/productview.xhtml?pid=PEP_2018_PEPANNRES&src=pt|archive-date=2019-07-27|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{refn|group=note|[[Swains Island]] in [[American Samoa]] (population 17) is the least-populous permanently-inhabited county-equivalent in the United States.<ref>https://www.britannica.com/place/Swains-Island Swains Island. Britannica.com. Retrieved September 5, 2019.</ref><ref>https://www2.census.gov/geo/pdfs/reference/GARM/Ch4GARM.pdf States, Counties, and Statistically Equivalent Entities (Chapter 4). Census.gov. Retrieved September 5, 2019.</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20170628232229/https://www.census.gov/geo/reference/codes/cou.html U.S. Census Bureau. 2010 FIPS Codes for Counties and County Equivalent Entities (archived). Retrieved September 5, 2019.</ref> [[Kingman Reef]], with a land area of 0.03 square kilometers,<ref>https://www.britannica.com/place/Kingman-Reef Britannica.com. Kingman Reef. Retrieved September 5, 2019.</ref> is the smallest county-equivalent in the U.S. by land area.}} The county encompasses the [[Kalaupapa Peninsula|Kalaupapa or Makanalua Peninsula]], on the north coast of the island of [[Molokai|Moloka{{okina}}i]]. The small peninsula is isolated from the rest of Moloka{{okina}}i by cliffs over a quarter-mile high&mdash;the only land access is a [[mule]] trail.\n\nBecause of the small population, Kalawao County does not have the functions of other Hawaii counties. Instead, it is a judicial district of [[Maui County, Hawaii|Maui County]], which includes the rest of the island of Moloka{{okina}}i. The county has no elected government.\n\nIt was developed and used from 1866 to 1969 for settlements for treatment of quarantined persons with [[Hansen's disease]] (leprosy).\n\n==History==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=January 2017}}\nThe [[Kingdom of Hawaii|Kingdom of Hawai{{okina}}i]], the [[Republic of Hawaii|Republic of Hawai{{okina}}i]], the [[Territory of Hawaii|territory]], and the state of Hawaii exiled persons suffering from [[Hansen's disease]] to the peninsula, from 1866 to 1969. The [[quarantine]] policy was lifted after effective [[Antibiotics|antibiotic]] treatments were developed that could be administered on an outpatient basis and patients could be rendered non-contagious.\n\nMany of the residents chose to remain on the peninsula, as they believed their disfigurements from the illness would make reintegration into society impossible. The state promised that they could live there for the rest of their lives. No new patients, or other permanent residents, were later admitted. Visitors are permitted only as part of official tours. State law prohibits anyone under the age of 16 from visiting or living there, although exceptions have been made for children visiting their relatives.\n\nThe [[Kalaupapa National Historical Park]] was established to preserve the county's history and environment. It is coterminous with the boundaries of Kalawao County.\n\n==Government==\nKalawao County lacks a local, county government. Instead, Kalawao County is administered by the [[Hawaii Department of Health]] because of the history of the settlement and current patients living there. Under Hawaiian state law, the Director of the Hawaii Department of Health, who is appointed by the [[Governor of Hawaii|Governor]], also serves as the [[Mayor of Kalawao County]].<ref name=hadvertiser>{{cite news|first=Robbie|last=Dingeman|title=Smallest county to ban smoking |url=http://the.honoluluadvertiser.com/article/2002/Oct/31/ln/ln22a.html |work=[[Honolulu Advertiser]] |date=2002-10-31 |accessdate=2014-01-02}}</ref><ref name=time>{{cite news|first=Nate|last=Rawlings|title=Hawaii Official Killed in Plane Crash |url=http://nation.time.com/2013/12/12/hawaii-official-killed-in-plane-crash/ |work=[[Time Magazine]] |date=2013-12-12 |accessdate=2014-01-02}}</ref><ref name=khon>{{cite news |first=Kristine |last=Uyeno |title=Hawaii Official Killed in Plane Crash |url=http://www.khon2.com/news/loretta-fuddy-committed-to-serving-others |work=[[KHON-TV|KHON]] |date=2013-12-12 |accessdate=2014-01-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140104142321/http://www.khon2.com/news/loretta-fuddy-committed-to-serving-others |archivedate=2014-01-04 }}</ref><ref name=hsa>{{cite news |first=Gregg K. |last=Kakesako |title=Pilot described 'catastrophic engine failure' in Molokai crash |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/breaking/235590541.html?id=235590541 |work=[[Honolulu Star Advertiser]] |date=2013-12-12 |accessdate=2014-01-02 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131221154659/http://www.staradvertiser.com/news/breaking/235590541.html?id=235590541 |archivedate=2013-12-21 |url-status=live }}</ref>  The Mayor holds executive powers within the county; the mayor also appoints a county [[Sheriffs in the United States|sheriff]], who is selected from local residents.<ref name=\"doh\">{{cite web |url=http://hawaii.gov/health/about/doh-info.html |title=Department of Health Administrative Offices |publisher=State of Hawai\u02bbi |accessdate=2010-09-28}}</ref> The only county statutes that apply to Kalawao County directly are those on matters of health.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chem.hawaii.edu/uham/counties.html|title=Hawaii's 4 (or 5) Counties|accessdate=2014-01-22}}</ref>\n\nKalawao is part of the First Judicial Circuit, which includes the entire island of [[Oahu]].<ref>\"The Judiciary - State of Hawaii - Annual Report - July 1, 1986 to June 30, 1987\". p16 and p26. https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/Digitization/109520NCJRS.pdf</ref> For the purpose of notarization, the designated venue for the First Judicial Circuit is \"State of Hawaii, City and County of Honolulu.\"\n\n==Geography==\nKalawao County is included in the [[Kahului, Hawaii|Kahului]]-[[Wailuku, Hawaii|Wailuku]]-[[Lahaina, Hawaii|Lahaina]], HI [[Metropolitan Statistical Area]].\n\nAccording to the [[U.S. Census Bureau]], the county has a total area of {{convert|53|sqmi}}, of which {{convert|12|sqmi}} is land and {{convert|41|sqmi}} (77.3%) is water.<ref name=\"GR1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2011-04-23|date=2011-02-12|title=US Gazetteer files: 2010, 2000, and 1990|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20020527061848/http://www.census.gov/geo/www/gazetteer/gazette.html|archive-date=2002-05-27|url-status=dead}}</ref> By land area, it is the [[County statistics of the United States#Smallest counties by land area nationwide|smallest true county in the United States]]; [[Falls Church, Virginia]] is smaller, but is an [[independent city]] with county-level governance and is not a county or part of one.\n\n===Kalaupapa Peninsula===\nKalaupapa Peninsula contains the county's only settlement, [[Kalaupapa, Hawaii|Kalaupapa]]. The Kalaupapa Peninsula developed from lava that erupted from the ocean floor near [[Kauhak\u014d Crater]] and spread outward, forming a low [[shield volcano]]. This was the most recent volcanic episode on the island and of the larger [[East Molokai|East Moloka{{okina}}i]] shield volcano, occurring after the formation of the cliffs by erosion.\n\n===Subdivisions===\n{{Outdated section|date = September 2014|reason = This section gives a population of 139, but the population is only 90}}\n\nKalawao County is composed of four [[ahupua\u02bba]]. From west to east:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.city-data.com/neighborhood/Kalaupapa-Ahupua-a-Kalaupapa-HI.html|title=Kalaupapa Ahupua`a neighborhood in Kalaupapa, Hawaii (HI), 96742 subdivision profile - real estate, apartments, condos, homes, community, population, jobs, income, streets|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.city-data.com/neighborhood/Waikolu-Ahupua-a-Kaunakakai-HI.html|title=Waikolu Ahupua`a neighborhood in Kaunakakai, Hawaii (HI), 96742 subdivision profile - real estate, apartments, condos, homes, community, population, jobs, income, streets|publisher=}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-style=\"background: #CCC;\"\n! align=\"left\" |''Ahupua\u02bba'' || Area<br />mi<sup>2</sup> || Area<br />km<sup>2</sup> || Population\n!Description\n|-\n| [[Kalaupapa, Hawaii|Kalaupapa]] || align=\"right\"|  2.079 || align=\"right\"|  5.385 || align=\"right\"| 122\n|West side of Kalaupapa peninsula. Includes a section of Moloka\u02bbi's coast further west\n|-\n| [[Makanalua, Hawaii|Makanalua]] || align=\"right\"|  3.229 || align=\"right\"|  8.363 || align=\"right\"| 8\n|Strip of land in the center of the peninsula that runs to its northern tip. Includes [[Kalaupapa Airport]].\n|-\n| [[Kalawao, Hawaii|Kalawao]] || align=\"right\"|  3.294 || align=\"right\"|  8.531 || align=\"right\"| 9\n|Eastern coast of Kalaupapa peninsula and Waialeia Valley to the southeast\n|-\n| [[Waikolu, Hawaii|Waikolu]] || align=\"right\"|  5.544 || align=\"right\"|  14.359 || align=\"right\"| 0\n|Includes namesake valley. Uninhabited.<ref>[http://manoa.hawaii.edu/hpicesu/techr/135/08.pdf Mark D. McCoy: ''The Lands of the Hina: An Archeological Overview and Assessment of Kalaupapa National Historical Park, Moloka{{Okina}}i,'' Chapter 8: Assessment] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110901015953/http://manoa.hawaii.edu/hpicesu/techr/135/08.pdf |date=2011-09-01 }}, Seite 33</ref>\n|-\n|-style=\"background: #DDD;\" | class=\"sortbottom\"\n|Kalawao County|| align=\"right\"| 14.146 || align=\"right\"| 36.638 || align=\"right\"| 139\n|\n|}\n\n===Demographics===\n{{US Census population\n|1900= 1177\n|1910= 785\n|1920= 667\n|1930= 605\n|1940= 446\n|1950= 340\n|1960= 279\n|1970= 172\n|1980= 144\n|1990= 130\n|2000= 147\n|2010= 90\n|estyear=2018\n|estimate=88\n|estref=<ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\">{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/programs-surveys/popest/data/tables.2018.html|title=Population and Housing Unit Estimates|accessdate=May 9, 2019}}</ref>\n|align-fn=center\n|footnote=U.S. Decennial Census<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|title=U.S. Decennial Census|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 28, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426102944/http://www.census.gov/prod/www/decennial.html|archivedate=April 26, 2015}}</ref><br />1790-1960<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mapserver.lib.virginia.edu|title=Historical Census Browser|publisher=University of Virginia Library|accessdate=June 28, 2014}}</ref> 1900-1990<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/hi190090.txt|title=Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 28, 2014}}</ref><br />1990-2000<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/www/cen2000/briefs/phc-t4/tables/tab02.pdf|title=Census 2000 PHC-T-4. Ranking Tables for Counties: 1990 and 2000|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 28, 2014}}</ref> 2010-2018<ref name=\"QF\">{{cite web|title=State & County QuickFacts|url=http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/15/15005.html|publisher=United States Census Bureau|accessdate=June 28, 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606183851/http://quickfacts.census.gov/qfd/states/15/15005.html|archivedate=June 6, 2011}}</ref>\n}}\n\nAs of the [[census]] of 2000,<ref name=\"GR2\">{{cite web|url=http://factfinder2.census.gov|publisher=[[United States Census Bureau]]|accessdate=2008-01-31|title=American FactFinder}}</ref> 147 people, 115 households, and 21 families resided in the county, declining to 90 inhabitants in 2010. The [[population density]] was 11 people per square mile (4/km<sup>2</sup>). The 172 housing units produced an average density of 13 per square&nbsp;mile (5/km<sup>2</sup>). The racial makeup of the county was 25.85% [[Race (U.S. census)|White]], 17.01% [[Race (U.S. census)|Asian]], 48.30% [[Race (U.S. census)|Pacific Islander]], 2.72% from [[race (U.S. census)|other races]], and 6.12% from two or more races. [[Race (U.S. census)|Hispanic]] or [[Race (U.S. census)|Latino]] of any race made up 4.08%.\n\n1.70% of households housed children under the age of 18. 16.50% were married couples living together. 2.60% had a female householder with no husband present. 80.90% were non-families. 79.10% of all households were made up of individuals and 31.30% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older. The average household size was 1.28 and the average family size was 2.27.\n\n2.00%  under the age of 18, 1.40% from 18 to 24, 18.40% from 25 to 44, 46.30% from 45 to 64, and 32.00% who were 65 years of age or older. The median age was 59 years. For every 100 females, there were 98.60 males. The population has declined since 1900:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/population/cencounts/hi190090.txt|title=Bureau of the Census: HAWAII. Population of Counties by Decennial Census: 1900 to 1990|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n<timeline>\nImageSize = width:600 height:200\nPlotArea = width:80% height:70% left:20% bottom:20%\nAlignBars = late\n\nDateFormat = yyyy\nPeriod = from:0 till:1200\nTimeAxis = orientation:vertical\nScaleMajor = increment:200 start:0\n\nPlotData=\n color:drabgreen \n bar:1900 from:start till:1177\n bar:1910 from:start till:785\n bar:1920 from:start till:667\n bar:1930 from:start till:605\n bar:1940 from:start till:446\n bar:1950 from:start till:370\n bar:1960 from:start till:279\n bar:1970 from:start till:172\n bar:1980 from:start till:144\n bar:1990 from:start till:130\n bar:2000 from:start till:147\n bar:2010 from:start till:90\n bar:2018 from:start till:88\n\nTextData=\n pos:(100,190) fontsize:M text:Population at censuses of 1900 through 2010\n</timeline>\n\nCurrent residents include 16 former patients,<ref>[http://www.hawaiinewsnow.com/story/29011284/kalaupapa-the-place-the-people-the-plan-for-the-future Planning for Kalaupapa's future means remembering its past]</ref> 40 federal employees who work on preservation projects, and some state-employed health workers.<ref>[https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2015/05/when-the-last-patient-dies/394163/ When the Last Patient Dies]</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nThe only access to Kalawao County is by air, or by a steep mule trail that descends 1,600 feet from the rest of Moloka{{okina}}i.  [[Kalaupapa Airport]] has scheduled air service to [[Molokai Airport|Moloka{{okina}}i Airport]] and to [[Honolulu Airport]].\n\nFreight is delivered to the county once a year, usually in July, by barge.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nps.gov/kala/historyculture/life2day.htm|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|title=Life Today in Kalaupapa|accessdate=January 22, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" class=\"toccolours\" style=\"float:right; margin-left:1em; font-size:95%;\"\n|+ '''Kalawao County vote<br /> by party in presidential elections'''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uselectionatlas.org/RESULTS/|title=Dave Leip's Atlas of U.S. Presidential Elections|first=David|last=Leip|website=uselectionatlas.org|accessdate=May 26, 2017}}</ref>\n|- style=''background:lightgrey;''\n! Year\n! [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n! [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n!Others\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2016 United States presidential election in Hawaii|2016]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|5.00% ''1''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''70.00%''' ''14''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|25.00% ''5''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2012 United States presidential election in Hawaii|2012]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|7.41% ''2''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''92.59%''' ''25''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|0% ''0''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2008 United States presidential election in Hawaii|2008]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|19.35% ''6''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''77.42%''' ''24''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|3.23% ''1''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2004 United States presidential election in Hawaii|2004]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|35.00% ''14''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''65.00%''' ''26''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|0% ''0''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[2000 United States presidential election in Hawaii|2000]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|24.44% ''11''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''66.67%''' ''30''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|8.89% ''4''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1996 United States presidential election in Hawaii|1996]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|20.63% ''13''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''73.02%''' ''46''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|6.35% ''4''\n|-\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''[[1992 United States presidential election in Hawaii|1992]]'''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Republican}}|32.00% ''24''\n|  style=''text-align:center;\" {{Party shading/Democratic}}|'''64.00%''' ''48''\n|  style=''text-align:center; background:honeyDew;''|4.00% ''3''\n|}\nLike the rest of the state, Kalawao County is a stronghold for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], despite the small number of total votes. It was the only county in the United States where the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] candidate in the [[2016 United States Presidential election]], [[Donald Trump]], finished in third only getting one vote; 70% of Kalawao's voters chose Democratic nominee [[Hillary Clinton]], and 25% of Kalawao voters cast their ballots for [[Green Party (United States)|Green]] candidate [[Jill Stein]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Statewide Precinct Detail |url=http://files.hawaii.gov/elections/files/results/2016/general/precinct.pdf |publisher=State of Hawaii Office of Elections |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikivoyage|Kalawao County}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Kalawao County, Molokai, Hawaii\n|North     = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n|Northeast = \n|East      = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n|Southeast = \n|South     = [[Maui County, Hawaii|Maui County]]\n|Southwest = \n|West      = [[Pacific Ocean]]\n|Northwest = \n}}\n\n{{Kalawao County, Hawaii}}\n{{Hawaii}}\n{{Western U.S. majority-minority counties}}{{Authority control}}\n{{coord|21|11|49|N|156|58|02|W|region:US-HI_type:adm2nd_source:dewiki|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Kalawao County, Hawaii| ]]\n[[Category:Molokai]]\n[[Category:Hawaii counties]]\n[[Category:1905 establishments in Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Populated places established in 1905]]\n[[Category:Maui County, Hawaii]]\n\u2190\u2014\n", "name_user": "SamIsMe31", "label": "safe", "comment": "Kalawao County is not included in that MSA per the latest Office of Management and Budget report", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kalawao_County,_Hawaii"}
