an),James Robert Mann\u2192James Robert Mann (Illinois politician),George Washington Smith\u2192George Washington Smith (congressman)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/59th_United_States_Congress"}
{"title_page": "Autonomous Government of Khorasan", "text_new": "{{More citations needed|date=August 2011}}\n{{Prose|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox Former Country\n|conventional_long_name = Autonomous State of Khorasan\n|common_name = Khorasan\n|status = Unrecognized\n|year_start = 1921\n|date_start = April\n|year_end = 1921\n|date_end = November\n|p1 = Persia\n|flag_p1 = State flag of Iran (1907-1933).svg\n|s1 = Persia\n|flag_s1 = State flag of Iran (1907-1933).svg\n|image_flag = State flag of Iran (1907-1933).svg\n|image_map = |image_map_caption = \n|capital = Mashhad\n|government_type = Military occupation\n|title_leader = President\n|leader1 = [[Mohammad Taqi Pessian]]\n|year_leader1 = 2 Apr &ndash; 3 Oct 1921\n|title_representative = Governor-General\n|representative1 = Mahmoud Khan Nowzari\n|year_representative1 = {{nowrap|4 Oct &ndash; Nov 1921 <small>(acting)</small>}}\n|representative2 = Ismail Khan Bahador\n|year_representative2 = 16 Nov 1921\n|stat_year1 = 1921\n|stat_area1 = 388332\n|stat_pop1 = \n|currency = \n}}\n\nThe '''Autonomous Government of Khorasan''' was a short-lived military state set up in what is now [[Iran]]. It was formally established on the April 2, 1921 and collapsed a few months later, on October 6, 1921. The area administered by the state was approximately 388,332 square kilometres and its capital was [[Mashhad]].\n\n== State information ==\n\n*'''Established: ''' 2 April 1921\n*'''Dissolved: ''' 6 October 1921\n*'''Capital: ''' [[Mashhad]], Khorasan\n*'''Major Administrative Towns: ''' [[Nishapur]], [[Quchan]], [[Bojnourd]], [[Sabzevar]], [[Torbat-e Heydarieh]], [[Torbat-e-Jam]], [[Ferdows]], [[Tabas]], [[Birjand]]\n*'''Type of Government: ''' [[Stratocracy|Military Government]], [[Secular]], [[Nationalist]]\n*'''Area: ''' 388,332&nbsp;km\u00b2(150,000 square miles) consisted of current Iranian provinces: [[Razavi Khorasan]], [[South Khorasan]], [[North Khorasan]], [[Golestan Province|Golestan]] as well as region of [[Sistan]]\n*'''Ethnic groups: ''' [[Persian people|Persian]], [[Khorasani Turkish]], [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]], [[Turkmen people|Turkmen]], [[T\u0101jik people|Tajik]], [[Hazara people|Hazara]], [[Baloch people|Baluch]], [[Arabic]], [[Aimak]], Barbari, [[Qarai Turks]]\n*'''Religions: ''' [[Shia Islam]], [[Sunni Islam]], [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]]\n*'''Import Trading Partners: ''' [[British India]]\n*'''Export Trading Partners: ''' [[RSFSR]], [[Afghanistan]]\n*'''Currency: ''' [[Iran|Persian]] [[Dinar]] [http://irancollection.alborzi.com/Qajarcoin/AhmadShah.htm Currency Photos]\n*'''Total Armed Forces: ''' 5,000 Gendarms in October, 1921\n\n== Government structure ==\n\n===Military Governor-General===\n* '''President of the National Committee of Khorasan (NCK): ''' [[Colonel Pesian|Colonel Mohammad Taqi Khan Pesyan]] 2 April 1921 to 3 October 1921\n* '''Acting Governor-General''' [[Mahmoud Nowzari|Major Mahmoud Khan Nowzari]] 4 October 1921 to early November, 1921 (Khorasan under Nowzari was not autonomous fully, as Nowzari had surrenderred to [[Persia]] and was simply acting Governor until arrival of Persia's appointed governor into [[Mashhad]].\n* '''Selfimposed Governor-General''' [[Ismail Bahador|Major Ismail Khan Bahador]] was second-in-command to Pesyan and after Pesyan's death he tried to maintain Khorasan's independence and continue Pesyan's path. He launched a coup against Nowzari on 16 October 1921 when he had him arrested and declared himself Governor-General of Khorasan which didn't last long as Nowzari received help and was rescued from prison.\n\n===Other senior government officials===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Official post !! Name !! Party affiliation\n|-\n| Commander of Armed Forces || [[Ismail Bahador|Major Ismail Khan Bahador]] || NCK\n|-\n| Senior Gendarmerie Commander || [[Mahmoud Nowzari|Major Mahmoud Khan Nowzari]] || NCK\n|-\n| Director of Revenues || {{flagicon|Belgium}} Monsieur [[L\u00e9on Dubois]] || ''none''\n|-\n| Revenue Accountant and Chief of Police<sup>a</sup> || [[Alam-od-dowleh]] || NCK\n|-\n| Chief of Police<sup>b</sup> || {{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Major Bronikovsky]] || ''none''\n|-\n| Mutavallibashi of the Shrine || [[Zahir-ol-Islam]] || NCK\n|-\n| ''Kargozar'' || [[Mutasim al-Saltaneh Farrokh]] || NCK\n|-\n| Owner of Tus Press || [[Mir Morteza]] || NCK\n|-\n| Chief Editor of Bahar Newspaper || [[Sheikh Ahmad Bahar]] || NCK\n|-\n| Founder of Democratic Party of Khorasan || [[Mohammad Taghi Bahar]] || DPK, NCK\n|-\n| Poet || [[Aref Qazvini]] || NCK\n|-\n| ''[[Ijtihad|Mojtahed]]'' || [[Mohammad Najafi Khorasani]]<sup>c</sup> || ''none''\n|-\n| Machine-gun Instructor || {{flagicon|Germany}} A German national || ''none''\n|-\n| Chief of Excise Department || || NCK\n|-\n| Chief of Post Office || || NCK\n|-\n| Chief of Telegraph Office || || NCK\n|-\n| Director of Education || || NCK\n|-\n| Chief of Customs Department || || NCK\n|-\n| Chief of Justice Department || || NCK\n|}\n{{smaller |a. From 24 August to 3 October.<br/>b. Until 24 August.<br/>c. Also known as \"Aghazadeh\".}}\n\n===Gendarmerie stations<ref>http://khschool.ir/Article/ViewArticle.asp?id=498&catname=%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%DB%8C%D8%AE&ActiveStateCode=300{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chief !! Location !! Name\n|-\n| [[Colonel Pessian]] || [[Mashhad]] || Ordu-ye Mashhad\n|-\n| Major Mahmoud Nowzari || [[Quchan]] || Ordu-ye Naderi\n|-\n| Major Ismail Bahador || [[Sabzevar]] || Ordu-ye Qader\n|-\n| Captain Mohammad Taqi Kavoussi || [[Torbat-e Heydarieh]] || Ordu-ye Kaveh\n|-\n| Captain Alireza Shamshir || [[Torbat-e Jam]] || Ordu-ye Shamshir\n|-\n| Captain Abdolrazaq Sepehri || [[Gonabad]] || Ordu-ye Barq\n|}\n\n===Regional Administrators and Tribal Chieftains===\n===Regional Administrators and Tribal Chieftains===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Administrator/Tribal Chief !! Region<br/>Capital !! Tribe/clan<br/>Ethnicity\n|-\n| [[Ismail Shawkat-ol-Molk II]] || [[Qayenat]]{{\\}}[[Sistan]]<br/>capital [[Birjand]] || Khozaima tribe<br/>[[Arab people|Arab]]\n|-\n| [[Salar Khan Baluch]] || [[Torbat-e Heydarieh]] || [[Baloch people|Baluch]]\n|-\n| [[Ibrahim Khan Baluch]] || Torbat-e Heydarieh || Baluch\n|-\n| [[Jafar Khan Qaraei]] || Torbat-e Heydarieh || Qaraei tribe<br/>[[Qaraei]]\n|-\n| [[Heydar Shah]] || || Barbari tribe<br/>Barbari\n|-\n| [[Mir Ali Ahmad]] || || Barbari tribe<br/>Barbari\n|-\n| [[Shawkat-od-Dowleh]] || capital [[Torbat-e Jam]] || Teymouri tribe<br/>[[Aimak]]\n|-\n| [[Shoja-ol-Molk]] || || Hazara tribe<br/>[[Hazara people|Hazara]]\n|-\n| [[Taj Mohammad Khan]] || [[Quchan]]<br/>capital Quchan || [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]]\n|-\n| [[Mohammad Ibrahim Khan Qaramanlu]] || Quchan<br/>capital Quchan || Qaramanlu clan<br/>Kurdish\n|}\n\n== Establishment ==\n\nOn April 2, 1921, Colonel Pesyan, Chief of Gendarmerie of Khorasan, along with his cousin General Heydargholli Pesyan, a commander of the Iranian Cossack Brigade, has [[Ahmad Qavam]] the Governor-general of Khorasan toppled in a military coup and has him arrested and sent to [[Tehran]]. Qavam and several other dominant figures in Khorasan were charged with Tax evasion charges which evidence were provided to Pesyan by a [[Belgian]] named Dubois who was Director of Revenue in Khorasan.\n\nWhile Qavam was in prison in Tehran, Pesyan was declared Governor-general of Khorasan and ruled Khorasan autonomously even though he was a supporter of [[Seyyed Zia'eddin Tabatabaee]] the Prime Minister of Persia.\n\nIn May 1921, Qavam is freed from prison and Tabatabaee is no longer Prime Minister. Qavam becomes Prime Minister and plans to take revenge on Pesyan. As of May 30, 1921 Pesyan declares that Khorasan is fully Autonomous and he establishes the '''National Committee of Khorasan''' or '''Komitey-e Melli-e Khorasan''' in Persian. The committee starts a program of plans and reforms, however they face some fierce opposition by some tribal and religious leaders.\n\n== Plans ==\n\n'''Commenced between 2 April to 25 May'''\n*Reform the military organisation of Khorasan and proclamation of martial law. The ''nizam'' (infantry) and Gendarmerie were combined to form this new force. New soldiers were heavily recruited for the new force. In April there were only 200 Gendarms while in October there were approximately 5,000.\n*Setup of a finance commission to investigate and assess revenue claims. This had outraged wealthy tribal chiefs and merchants.\n*Reform of the shrine administration, this included steps to be taken against those shrine administrators who had consumed vast amount of shrine's revenues.\n*Subsidisine two local newspapers ''Sharq-e-Iran'' (The East of Iran) and ''Mihr-e-Monir'' (The Shining Sun) to support the government of Seyed Zia Tabatabaei.\n\n'''Commenced between 26 May to 6 Oct'''\n*Impose of censorship in the telegraph office.\n*Series of arrest of persons believed to have been collaborating with Persia's Central Government of Ahmad Qavam.\n*''Kumiteye Melli-e Khorasan'' (National Committee of Khorasan) issued a manifesto on 15 September 1921, and prepared a proclamation declaring Khorasan a republic which was postponed by Colonel Pesyan and never implemented.\n*Sold a large amount of grain to a Bolshevik Food Purchasing Commission.\n*Extracted forced loans from the wealthy and auctioned off the belongings of the defeated tribal chiefs.\n*Encouraged anti-British stance, pro-Soviet ideas and Persian Nationalist beliefs.\n*Imposed a poll tax on all travellers leaving Mashhad and 10% Tax on all exports.\n*Encouraged export of goods to Afghanistan and Soviet Union.\n*Established a local Bank in September 1921.\n*Striking of its own coinage was also considered.\n*Steps for the inception of a Department of Education were taken, Colonel Pesyan himself gave money in the interests of female schooling.\n\n== Battles ==\n\nSeveral tribal leaders who had lost most of their wealth and belongings due to Pesyan's reform programs were supported by Qavam's government.  Therefore, on August 11, 1921 the first battle took place between a detachment of Gendarmes in a village near [[Kariz, Bamyan|Kariz]] on [[Afghanistan]] border and forces of [[Hazara people|Hazara]] chief Shuja al-Mulk. Gendarmes defeated and fled to [[Mashhad]]. This defeat results in appointment of Shawkat al-Dowlah a rival of Shuja al-Mulk as Governor of [[Torbat-e-Jam]] with a task to deal with disturbances and a sending of strong numerous gendarme forces on August 20, 1921.\n\nIn September, 1921 Gendarme forces from [[Kariz, Bamyan|Kariz]], [[Torbat-e-Jam]], [[Torbat-e Heydarieh]] defeated the strong tribal confederatory force of [[Hazara people|Hazara]], [[Baloch people|Baluch]], Barbari and [[Qarai Turks]], whose leaders were Shuja al-Mulk, Seyed Heydar Barbari, Salar Khan Baluch, Mir Ali Ahmad Barbari, Ibrahim Khan Baluch and Jafar Khan Qaraei in a battle which took place in [[Bakharz]]. Shuja fled to Afghanistan and the tribal disturbances in the south-east were stopped.\n\nOctober 3, 1921 Pesyan himself took battle leading his 150 Gendarmes to fight a [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] coalition tribal force which had more than 1,000 men, led by Sardar of [[Bojnurd]] and Taj Mohammad Khan of [[Quchan]], who were also financially and militarily aided by the British and Persian government of Ahmad Qavam.  Pesyan fought bravely with only 60 bullets, however he and his small force were circled by the Kurds and were martyred.  Pesyan's head was cut off as proof of his death and sent to Qavam.\n\n== Collapse ==\n\nAfter Pesyan's death, the committee was no longer united.  A new rivalry started between Nowzari and Ismail Khan Bahador, who were Pesyan's partisans.  Nowzari managed to take charge of Khorasan and he surrendered to Persia's government.  In November, 1921 a strong military force of Gendarmes and Cossacks arrived in [[Mashhad]] and handed the administrative duties to the newly appointed Governor-General of the province.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''An Experiment in Revolutionary Nationalism: The Rebellion of Colonel Muhammad Taqi Khan Pasyan in Mashhad, April\u2013October 1921'', Stephanie Cronin, Journal of Middle Eastern Studies, Vol.33, No. 4 October 1997, pp.&nbsp;693\u2013750.\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* [https://books.google.nl/books/about/Soldiers_Shahs_and_Subalterns_in_Iran.html?id=WPOADAAAQBAJ Soldiers, Shahs and Subalterns in Iran: Opposition, Protest and Revolt, 1921-1941]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.iichs.org/index.asp?id=45&doc_cat=1 Institute of Iranian Contemporary History Studies]\n* [http://www.tabriz-info.com/tabriz/shahrdaran/bahdor-esmael.htm Tabriz-Info]\n{{Unrecognized states in the Iranian territory}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Autonomous Government Of Khorasan}}\n[[Category:1921 disestablishments in Asia]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1921]]\n[[Category:History of North Khorasan Province]]\n[[Category:History of South Khorasan Province]]\n[[Category:History of Razavi Khorasan Province]]\n[[Category:History of Golestan Province]]\n[[Category:20th century in Iran]]\n[[Category:1921 in Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{More citations needed|date=August 2011}}\n{{Prose|date=July 2018}}\n{{Infobox Former Country\n|conventional_long_name = Autonomous State of Khorasan\n|common_name = Khorasan\n|status = Unrecognized\n|year_start = 1921\n|date_start = April\n|year_end = 1921\n|date_end = November\n|p1 = Persia\n|flag_p1 = State flag of Iran (1907-1933).svg\n|s1 = Persia\n|flag_s1 = State flag of Iran (1907-1933).svg\n|image_flag = State flag of Iran (1907-1933).svg\n|image_map = |image_map_caption = \n|capital = Mashhad\n|government_type = Military occupation\n|title_leader = President\n|leader1 = [[Mohammad Taqi Pessian]]\n|year_leader1 = 2 Apr &ndash; 3 Oct 1921\n|title_representative = Governor-General\n|representative1 = Mahmoud Khan Nowzari\n|year_representative1 = {{nowrap|4 Oct &ndash; Nov 1921 <small>(acting)</small>}}\n|representative2 = Ismail Khan Bahador\n|year_representative2 = 16 Nov 1921\n|stat_year1 = 1921\n|stat_area1 = 388332\n|stat_pop1 = \n|currency = \n}}\n\nThe '''Autonomous Government of Khorasan''' was a short-lived military state set up in what is now [[Iran]]. It was formally established on the April 2, 1921 and collapsed a few months later, on October 6, 1921. The area administered by the state was approximately 388,332 square kilometres and its capital was [[Mashhad]].\n\n== State information ==\n\n*'''Established: ''' 2 April 1921\n*'''Dissolved: ''' 6 October 1921\n*'''Capital: ''' [[Mashhad]], Khorasan\n*'''Major Administrative Towns: ''' [[Nishapur]], [[Quchan]], [[Bojnourd]], [[Sabzevar]], [[Torbat-e Heydarieh]], [[Torbat-e-Jam]], [[Ferdows]], [[Tabas]], [[Birjand]]\n*'''Type of Government: ''' [[Stratocracy|Military Government]], [[Secular]], [[Nationalist]]\n*'''Area: ''' 388,332&nbsp;km\u00b2(150,000 square miles) consisted of current Iranian provinces: [[Razavi Khorasan]], [[South Khorasan]], [[North Khorasan]], [[Golestan Province|Golestan]] as well as region of [[Sistan]]\n*'''Ethnic groups: ''' [[Persian people|Persian]], [[Khorasani Turkish]], [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]], [[Turkmen people|Turkmen]], [[T\u0101jik people|Tajik]], [[Hazara people|Hazara]], [[Baloch people|Baluch]], [[Arabic]], [[Aimak]], Barbari, [[Qarai Turks]]\n*'''Religions: ''' [[Shia Islam]], [[Sunni Islam]], [[Bah\u00e1'\u00ed Faith]]\n*'''Import Trading Partners: ''' [[British India]]\n*'''Export Trading Partners: ''' [[RSFSR]], [[Afghanistan]]\n*'''Currency: ''' [[Iran|Persian]] [[Dinar]] [http://irancollection.alborzi.com/Qajarcoin/AhmadShah.htm Currency Photos]\n*'''Total Armed Forces: ''' 5,000 Gendarms in October, 1921\n\n== Government structure ==\n\n===Military Governor-General===\n* '''President of the National Committee of Khorasan(NCK): ''' [[Colonel Pesian|Colonel Mohammad Taqi Khan Pesyan]] 2 April 1921 to 3 October 1921\n* '''Acting Governor-General''' [[Mahmoud Nowzari|Major Mahmoud Khan Nowzari]] 4 October 1921 to early November, 1921 (Khorasan under Nowzari was not autonomous fully, as Nowzari had surrenderred to [[Persia]] and was simply acting Governor until arrival of Persia's appointed governor into [[Mashhad]].\n* '''Selfimposed Governor-General''' [[Ismail Bahador|Major Ismail Khan Bahador]] was second-in-command to Pesyan and after Pesyan's death he tried to maintain Khorasan's independence and continue Pesyan's path. He launched a coup against Nowzari on 16 October 1921 when he had him arrested and declared himself Governor-General of Khorasan which didn't last long as Nowzari received help and was rescued from prison.\n\n===Other senior government officials===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Official post !! Name !! Party affiliation\n|-\n| Commander of Armed Forces || [[Ismail Bahador|Major Ismail Khan Bahador]] || NCK\n|-\n| Senior Gendarmerie Commander || [[Mahmoud Nowzari|Major Mahmoud Khan Nowzari]] || NCK\n|-\n| Director of Revenues || {{flagicon|Belgium}} Monsieur [[L\u00e9on Dubois]] || ''none''\n|-\n| Revenue Accountant and Chief of Police<sup>a</sup> || [[Alam-od-dowleh]] || NCK\n|-\n| Chief of Police<sup>b</sup> || {{flagicon|Sweden}} [[Major Bronikovsky]] || ''none''\n|-\n| Mutavallibashi of the Shrine || [[Zahir-ol-Islam]] || NCK\n|-\n| ''Kargozar'' || [[Mutasim al-Saltaneh Farrokh]] || NCK\n|-\n| Owner of Tus Press || [[Mir Morteza]] || NCK\n|-\n| Chief Editor of Bahar Newspaper || [[Sheikh Ahmad Bahar]] || NCK\n|-\n| Founder of Democratic Party of Khorasan || [[Mohammad Taghi Bahar]] || DPK, NCK\n|-\n| Poet || [[Aref Qazvini]] || NCK\n|-\n| ''[[Ijtihad|Mojtahed]]'' || [[Mohammad Najafi Khorasani]]<sup>c</sup> || ''none''\n|-\n| Machine-gun Instructor || {{flagicon|Germany}} A German national || ''none''\n|-\n| Chief of Excise Department || || NCK\n|-\n| Chief of Post Office || || NCK\n|-\n| Chief of Telegraph Office || || NCK\n|-\n| Director of Education || || NCK\n|-\n| Chief of Customs Department || || NCK\n|-\n| Chief of Justice Department || || NCK\n|}\n{{smaller |a. From 24 August to 3 October.<br/>b. Until 24 August.<br/>c. Also known as \"Aghazadeh\".}}\n\n===Gendarmerie stations<ref>http://khschool.ir/Article/ViewArticle.asp?id=498&catname=%D8%AA%D8%A7%D8%B1%DB%8C%D8%AE&ActiveStateCode=300{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Chief !! Location !! Name\n|-\n| [[Colonel Pessian]] || [[Mashhad]] || Ordu-ye Mashhad\n|-\n| Major Mahmoud Nowzari || [[Quchan]] || Ordu-ye Naderi\n|-\n| Major Ismail Bahador || [[Sabzevar]] || Ordu-ye Qader\n|-\n| Captain Mohammad Taqi Kavoussi || [[Torbat-e Heydarieh]] || Ordu-ye Kaveh\n|-\n| Captain Alireza Shamshir || [[Torbat-e Jam]] || Ordu-ye Shamshir\n|-\n| Captain Abdolrazaq Sepehri || [[Gonabad]] || Ordu-ye Barq\n|}\n\n===Regional Administrators and Tribal Chieftains===\n===Regional Administrators and Tribal Chieftains===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Administrator/Tribal Chief !! Region<br/>Capital !! Tribe/clan<br/>Ethnicity\n|-\n| [[Ismail Shawkat-ol-Molk II]] || [[Qayenat]]{{\\}}[[Sistan]]<br/>capital [[Birjand]] || Khozaima tribe<br/>[[Arab people|Arab]]\n|-\n| [[Salar Khan Baluch]] || [[Torbat-e Heydarieh]] || [[Baloch people|Baluch]]\n|-\n| [[Ibrahim Khan Baluch]] || Torbat-e Heydarieh || Baluch\n|-\n| [[Jafar Khan Qaraei]] || Torbat-e Heydarieh || Qaraei tribe<br/>[[Qaraei]]\n|-\n| [[Heydar Shah]] || || Barbari tribe<br/>Barbari\n|-\n| [[Mir Ali Ahmad]] || || Barbari tribe<br/>Barbari\n|-\n| [[Shawkat-od-Dowleh]] || capital [[Torbat-e Jam]] || Teymouri tribe<br/>[[Aimak]]\n|-\n| [[Shoja-ol-Molk]] || || Hazara tribe<br/>[[Hazara people|Hazara]]\n|-\n| [[Taj Mohammad Khan]] || [[Quchan]]<br/>capital Quchan || [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]]\n|-\n| [[Mohammad Ibrahim Khan Qaramanlu]] || Quchan<br/>capital Quchan || Qaramanlu clan<br/>Kurdish\n|}\n\n== Establishment ==\n\nOn April 2, 1921, Colonel Pesyan, Chief of Gendarmerie of Khorasan, along with his cousin General Heydargholli Pesyan, a commander of the Iranian Cossack Brigade, has [[Ahmad Qavam]] the Governor-general of Khorasan toppled in a military coup and has him arrested and sent to [[Tehran]]. Qavam and several other dominant figures in Khorasan were charged with Tax evasion charges which evidence were provided to Pesyan by a [[Belgian]] named Dubois who was Director of Revenue in Khorasan.\n\nWhile Qavam was in prison in Tehran, Pesyan was declared Governor-general of Khorasan and ruled Khorasan autonomously even though he was a supporter of [[Seyyed Zia'eddin Tabatabaee]] the Prime Minister of Persia.\n\nIn May 1921, Qavam is freed from prison and Tabatabaee is no longer Prime Minister. Qavam becomes Prime Minister and plans to take revenge on Pesyan. As of May 30, 1921 Pesyan declares that Khorasan is fully Autonomous and he establishes the '''National Committee of Khorasan''' or '''Komitey-e Melli-e Khorasan''' in Persian. The committee starts a program of plans and reforms, however they face some fierce opposition by some tribal and religious leaders.\n\n== Plans ==\n\n'''Commenced between 2 April to 25 May'''\n*Reform the military organisation of Khorasan and proclamation of martial law. The ''nizam'' (infantry) and Gendarmerie were combined to form this new force. New soldiers were heavily recruited for the new force. In April there were only 200 Gendarms while in October there were approximately 5,000.\n*Setup of a finance commission to investigate and assess revenue claims. This had outraged wealthy tribal chiefs and merchants.\n*Reform of the shrine administration, this included steps to be taken against those shrine administrators who had consumed vast amount of shrine's revenues.\n*Subsidisine two local newspapers ''Sharq-e-Iran'' (The East of Iran) and ''Mihr-e-Monir'' (The Shining Sun) to support the government of Seyed Zia Tabatabaei.\n\n'''Commenced between 26 May to 6 Oct'''\n*Impose of censorship in the telegraph office.\n*Series of arrest of persons believed to have been collaborating with Persia's Central Government of Ahmad Qavam.\n*''Kumiteye Melli-e Khorasan'' (National Committee of Khorasan) issued a manifesto on 15 September 1921, and prepared a proclamation declaring Khorasan a republic which was postponed by Colonel Pesyan and never implemented.\n*Sold a large amount of grain to a Bolshevik Food Purchasing Commission.\n*Extracted forced loans from the wealthy and auctioned off the belongings of the defeated tribal chiefs.\n*Encouraged anti-British stance, pro-Soviet ideas and Persian Nationalist beliefs.\n*Imposed a poll tax on all travellers leaving Mashhad and 10% Tax on all exports.\n*Encouraged export of goods to Afghanistan and Soviet Union.\n*Established a local Bank in September 1921.\n*Striking of its own coinage was also considered.\n*Steps for the inception of a Department of Education were taken, Colonel Pesyan himself gave money in the interests of female schooling.\n\n== Battles ==\n\nSeveral tribal leaders who had lost most of their wealth and belongings due to Pesyan's reform programs were supported by Qavam's government.  Therefore, on August 11, 1921 the first battle took place between a detachment of Gendarmes in a village near [[Kariz, Bamyan|Kariz]] on [[Afghanistan]] border and forces of [[Hazara people|Hazara]] chief Shuja al-Mulk. Gendarmes defeated and fled to [[Mashhad]]. This defeat results in appointment of Shawkat al-Dowlah a rival of Shuja al-Mulk as Governor of [[Torbat-e-Jam]] with a task to deal with disturbances and a sending of strong numerous gendarme forces on August 20, 1921.\n\nIn September, 1921 Gendarme forces from [[Kariz, Bamyan|Kariz]], [[Torbat-e-Jam]], [[Torbat-e Heydarieh]] defeated the strong tribal confederatory force of [[Hazara people|Hazara]], [[Baloch people|Baluch]], Barbari and [[Qarai Turks]], whose leaders were Shuja al-Mulk, Seyed Heydar Barbari, Salar Khan Baluch, Mir Ali Ahmad Barbari, Ibrahim Khan Baluch and Jafar Khan Qaraei in a battle which took place in [[Bakharz]]. Shuja fled to Afghanistan and the tribal disturbances in the south-east were stopped.\n\nOctober 3, 1921 Pesyan himself took battle leading his 150 Gendarmes to fight a [[Kurdish people|Kurdish]] coalition tribal force which had more than 1,000 men, led by Sardar of [[Bojnurd]] and Taj Mohammad Khan of [[Quchan]], who were also financially and militarily aided by the British and Persian government of Ahmad Qavam.  Pesyan fought bravely with only 60 bullets, however he and his small force were circled by the Kurds and were martyred.  Pesyan's head was cut off as proof of his death and sent to Qavam.\n\n== Collapse ==\n\nAfter Pesyan's death, the committee was no longer united.  A new rivalry started between Nowzari and Ismail Khan Bahador, who were Pesyan's partisans.  Nowzari managed to take charge of Khorasan and he surrendered to Persia's government.  In November, 1921 a strong military force of Gendarmes and Cossacks arrived in [[Mashhad]] and handed the administrative duties to the newly appointed Governor-General of the province.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''An Experiment in Revolutionary Nationalism: The Rebellion of Colonel Muhammad Taqi Khan Pasyan in Mashhad, April\u2013October 1921'', Stephanie Cronin, Journal of Middle Eastern Studies, Vol.33, No. 4 October 1997, pp.&nbsp;693\u2013750.\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* [https://books.google.nl/books/about/Soldiers_Shahs_and_Subalterns_in_Iran.html?id=WPOADAAAQBAJ Soldiers, Shahs and Subalterns in Iran: Opposition, Protest and Revolt, 1921-1941]\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.iichs.org/index.asp?id=45&doc_cat=1 Institute of Iranian Contemporary History Studies]\n* [http://www.tabriz-info.com/tabriz/shahrdaran/bahdor-esmael.htm Tabriz-Info]\n{{Unrecognized states in the Iranian territory}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Autonomous Government Of Khorasan}}\n[[Category:1921 disestablishments in Asia]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1921]]\n[[Category:History of North Khorasan Province]]\n[[Category:History of South Khorasan Province]]\n[[Category:History of Razavi Khorasan Province]]\n[[Category:History of Golestan Province]]\n[[Category:20th century in Iran]]\n[[Category:1921 in Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Brozozo", "label": "safe", "comment": "copy edit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Autonomous_Government_of_Khorasan"}
{"title_page": "Uro\u0161 Kova\u010devi\u0107", "text_new": "{{Infobox volleyball player\n| name             = Uro\u0161 Kova\u010devi\u0107\n| image            = Uros Kovacevic (Legavolley 2019).jpg\n| imagesize        = \n| caption          =\n| nationality      = {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Serbia|Serbian]]\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1993|5|6}}\n| birth_place      = [[Kraljevo]], [[Serbia and Montenegro|FR Yugoslavia]], [[Serbia]]\n| height           = 1.97 m\n| weight           = 90 kg\n| spike            = 340 cm\n| block            = 310 cm\n| position         = Outside hitter\n| currentnumber    = 93\n| currentclub      = {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Trentino Volley|Diatec Trentino]]\n| years            = 2003\u20132010<br>2010\u20132012<br>2012\u20132015<br>2015\u20132017<br>2016<br>2017\u20132020\n| clubs            = {{flagicon|SRB}} Ribnica Kraljevo<br> {{flagicon|SLO}} [[ACH Volley]]<br> {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Modena Volley|Casa Modena]]<br> {{flagicon|ITA}} [[BluVolley Verona|Calzedonia Verona]]<br> {{flagicon|QAT}} [[Al Arabi Qatar (volleyball)|Al Arabi]]<br> {{flagicon|ITA}} [[Trentino Volley|Diatec Trentino]]\n| nationalyears    = 2011\u2013\n| nationalteam     = {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n| medaltemplates   =\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Men's European Volleyball Championship|European Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2019 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2019 Belgium/France/Netherlands/Slovenia]]|}}\n{{MedalGold|[[2011 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2011 Austria/Czech Republic]]|}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[2017 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2017 Poland]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Volleyball World League|World League]]}}\n{{Medal|Gold|[[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|2016 Krak\u00f3w]]|}}\n{{MedalSilver|[[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|2015 Rio de Janeiro]]|}}\n}}\n\n'''Uro\u0161 Kova\u010devi\u0107''' ({{lang-sr-cyrl|\u0423\u0440\u043e\u0448 \u041a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b}}, born 6 May 1993) is a [[Serbia|Serbian]] [[volleyball]] player, a member of [[Serbia men's national volleyball team]] and [[Italy|Italian]] club [[Trentino Volley]], gold medalist of the [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|2016 World League]], [[2011 Men's European Volleyball Championship|European Champion 2011]], [[2019 Men's European Volleyball Championship|European Champion 2019]].\n\n==Personal life==\nHe has two older brothers: Savo and [[Nikola Kova\u010devi\u0107|Nikola]] (born 1983). Nikola is also a [[volleyball player]].\n\n===National team===\nHe is a gold medalist of [[2011 Men's European Volleyball Championship|European Championship 2011]].<ref>[http://www.cev.eu/Competition-Area/CompetitionNews.aspx?ID=14&NewsID=11000&TagType=0&TagContent=0&NewsType=0&Paging=0&Sd=1/1/1900&Ed=1/1/1900 ''Serbia is the 2011 European champion!''] \u2013 cev.eu \u2013 18-09-2011</ref> In 2011 Kova\u010devi\u0107 received the [[Awards of Olympic Committee of Serbia|award]] from [[Olympic Committee of Serbia]] and [[DSL Sport]] for the best young athlete.<ref>[http://www.mondo.rs/s228716/Ostali_sportovi/Sport-_Novak_Djokovic_ponovo_najbolji.html ''\"Sport\": Novak \u0110okovi\u0107 ponovo najbolji''] \u2013 mondo.rs \u2013 26-12-2011</ref> He was a member of the national team at the [[2012 Summer Olympics]] in [[London]]. On July 19, 2015 [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbian national team]] with him in squad went to the final of [[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|World League]], but they lost with [[France men's national volleyball team|France]] 0\u20133 and achieved silver medal.<ref>[http://worldleague.2015.fivb.com/en/intercontinental-group1/news/france-upset-serbia-to-claim-first-world?id=55058 ''France upset Serbia to claim first World League title''] \u2013 fivb.org \u2013 19-07-2015</ref><ref>[http://worldleague.2015.fivb.com/en/intercontinental-group1/news/france-prevail-over-serbia-to-claim-gold?id=55060 ''France prevail over Serbia to claim gold; USA finish third''] \u2013 fivb.org \u2013 19-07-2015</ref> He was named MVP of the [[2019 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2019 European Championship]] where Serbia won the gold medal.<ref>{{cite news |title=\u0423\u0440\u043e\u0448 \u041a\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0438\u045b \u041c\u0412\u041f \u0448\u0430\u043c\u043f\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 |url=http://www.rts.rs/page/sport/ci/story/34/odbojka/3678294/uros-kovacevic-mvp-sampionata.html |accessdate=3 October 2019 |work=www.rts.rs |date=29 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Sporting achievements==\n* '''[[CEV Cup]]'''\n** [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2018\u201319 Men's CEV Cup|2018/2019]] \u2013 with [[Trentino Volley|Itas Trentino]]\n\n* '''[[CEV Challenge Cup]]'''\n** [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] [[2015\u201316 CEV Challenge Cup|2015/2016]] \u2013 with [[BluVolley Verona|Calzedonia Verona]]\n\n* '''[[FIVB Volleyball Men's Club World Championship|FIVB Club World Championship]]'''\n** [[File:Gold medal world centered-2.svg|16px]] [[2018 FIVB Volleyball Men's Club World Championship|Poland 2018]] \u2013 with [[Trentino Volley|Itas Trentino]]\n\n* '''[[AVC Club Volleyball Championship|AVC Asian Club Championship]]'''\n** [[File:Silver medal asia.svg|16px]] [[2016 Asian Men's Club Volleyball Championship|Myanmar 2016]] \u2013 with [[Al Arabi Qatar (volleyball)|Al Arabi Qatar]]\n\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''2010/2011''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Slovenian Cup, with [[ACH Volley]]\n** '''2010/2011''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Slovenian Volleyball League|Slovenian Championship]], with [[ACH Volley]]\n** '''2011/2012''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Slovenian Cup, with [[ACH Volley]]\n** '''2011/2012''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Slovenian Volleyball League|Slovenian Championship]], with [[ACH Volley]]\n** '''2014/2015''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Italian Cup, with [[Modena Volley|Parmareggio Modena]]\n** '''2014/2015''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2014\u201315 Men's Volleyball Serie A1|Italian Championship]], with [[Modena Volley|Parmareggio Modena]]\n** '''2018/2019''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Italian Volleyball League|Italian Championship]], with [[Trentino Volley|Itas Trentino]]\n\n* '''National team'''\n** '''2009''' [[File:Silver medal europe.svg|16px]] [[Boys' Youth European Volleyball Championship|CEV U19 European Championship]]\n** '''2009''' [[File:Gold medal world centered-2.svg|16px]] [[2009 FIVB Volleyball Boys' U19 World Championship|FIVB U19 World Championship]]\n** '''2010''' [[File:Bronze medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2010 Men's Junior European Volleyball Championship|CEV U21 European Championship]]\n** '''2011''' [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16px]] [[Boys' Youth European Volleyball Championship|CEV U19 European Championship]]\n** '''2011''' [[File:Bronze medal world centered-2.svg|16px]] [[2011 FIVB Volleyball Men's U21 World Championship|FIVB U21 World Championship]]\n** '''2011''' [[File:Gold medal world centered-2.svg|16px]] [[2011 FIVB Volleyball Boys' U19 World Championship|FIVB U19 World Championship]]\n** '''2011''' [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2011 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]]\n** '''2013''' [[File:Silver medal world centered-2.svg|16px]] [[2013 FIVB Volleyball Men's U23 World Championship|FIVB U23 World Championship]]\n** '''2015''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2015 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n** '''2016''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2016 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]]\n** '''2017''' [[File:Bronze medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2017 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]]\n** '''2019''' [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16px]]  [[2019 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]]\n\n===Individually===\n* '''2011:''' CEV U19 European Championship \u2013 Most Valuable Player\n* '''2011:''' [[2011 FIVB Volleyball Boys' U19 World Championship|FIVB U19 World Championship]] \u2013 Most Valuable Player\n* '''2011:''' [[Awards of Olympic Committee of Serbia#Young Athlete of The Year|Award of Olympic Committee]] \u2013 Young Athlete of The Year\n* '''2011:''' Young Athlete of The Year by [[DSL Sport]]\n* '''2013:''' [[2013 FIVB Volleyball Men's U23 World Championship|FIVB U23 World Championship]] \u2013 Best Outside Spiker\n* '''2016:''' [[2016 Memorial of Hubert Jerzy Wagner|Memorial of Hubert Jerzy Wagner]] \u2013 Best Outside Spiker\n* '''2016:''' [[2016 Asian Men's Club Volleyball Championship|Asian Club Championship]] \u2013 Best Outside Spiker\n* '''2018:''' [[2018 FIVB Volleyball Men's Club World Championship|FIVB Club World Championship]] \u2013 Best Outside Spiker\n* '''2019:''' [[2019 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Volleyball Championship]] \u2013 Best Outside Spiker\n* '''2019:''' [[2019 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Volleyball Championship]] \u2013 Most Valuable Player \n* '''2019:''' CEV Male Volleyball Player of the Year<ref>{{cite news |title=Top achievements honoured at European Volleyball Gala |url=https://www.cev.eu/News.aspx?NewsID=29910&ID=1 |accessdate=25 October 2019 |work=www.cev.eu |date=25 October 2019}}</ref>\n* '''2019:'''  Male Serbian Volleyball Player of the Year<ref>{{cite news |title=Male Serbian Volleyball Player of the Year|url=https://www.ossrb.org/sve-vesti/oss-kategorija/vesti-iz-oss/12367-tijana-boskovic-i-uros-kovacevic-najbolji-u-2019-hena-kurtagic-i-davide-kovac-najperspektivniji.html |accessdate=28 December 2019 |work=www.ossrb.org |date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.legavolley.it/player/CEB-KLE-92 legavolley.it Player profile] \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{commons}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|aw}}\n{{succession box |\n  | before = [[Olivera Moldovan|Olivera]] and <br>[[Nikolina Moldovan]]\n  | after = [[Amela Terzi\u0107]]\n  | title = {{flagicon|SRB}} [[